WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:01.320
Okay.

00:00:01.320 --> 00:00:03.520
Thank you all for being here today.

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:06.280
I'm excited to share an R package with you all

00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:10.280
that we've been working on called Docorator.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:12.140
So I'll start by saying that this presentation

00:00:12.140 --> 00:00:15.600
is my personal opinion and not that of my organization.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:20.980
So in my house lately, my son has taken a liking

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:23.600
to home renovation shows,

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:25.799
and especially this one called Fixer Upper.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:28.000
I don't know if you guys have seen it before,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
but if you haven't, the premise is that the hosts,

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:37.880
Chip and Joanna, they work with a different set of clients

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:40.320
in every episode, and they help them pick out a house

00:00:40.320 --> 00:00:42.279
that's pretty worse for wear,

00:00:42.279 --> 00:00:45.560
and they spend the episode redesigning,

00:00:46.439 --> 00:00:49.680
giving it a facelift, gutting out some pieces of it

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:52.840
until it becomes a total dream home in the end.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:54.919
And it's kind of addicting,

00:00:54.919 --> 00:00:57.880
even though pretty much every episode

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:02.520
has the same storyline with that transformation.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:07.519
And so I work in Pharma, where my role is to help enable

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.080
teams and people using R for the first time,

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:15.120
and even people who are a little further along.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:19.440
So just helping people on their open source journey.

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:21.480
And more broadly, Pharma is going through

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:25.239
a pretty significant movement towards open source adoption.

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:27.199
It's pretty cool to see.

00:01:27.199 --> 00:01:29.919
Lots and lots of organizations are getting on board.

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:32.120
We had a summit meeting on Monday,

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:33.760
where everyone kind of came in

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:35.639
and talked about challenges together.

00:01:35.639 --> 00:01:38.680
So a lot of commonalities there.

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:42.440
People, I'm sorry, organizations are going through

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:45.720
this process, and they're not only upskilling,

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:49.120
but they're also looking at their legacy systems

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:52.519
and tooling and seeing, okay, what do we need to change?

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:57.320
What do we need to revamp and transform here?

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:00.480
But yeah, a lot of commonalities, and because of this,

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:05.360
we have a lot of community efforts towards shared tooling.

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:09.119
So a few years ago, the Pharmaverse came to be.

00:02:09.119 --> 00:02:12.720
And the Pharmaverse is a collection of R packages.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:15.160
It's like an ecosystem of R packages

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:18.559
that cover the routine milestones

00:02:18.559 --> 00:02:21.520
that many pharma companies have to cover,

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:27.559
like standard data transformations,

00:02:28.039 --> 00:02:32.160
all the way through to standard-looking tables and figures,

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:34.440
just the routine steps.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:38.039
So over the past few years, a lot of progress has been made.

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:41.759
And today, lots of organizations are well-poised

00:02:41.759 --> 00:02:44.080
to cover their bases with these packages.

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:46.399
And they work together in conjunction

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:47.800
with the Tidyverse and beyond,

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:51.119
which is why you see them all kind of coexisting here.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:54.160
But the Pharmaverse isn't static.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:58.320
It's ever-evolving, it's expanding all the time

00:02:58.320 --> 00:02:59.720
because there's a lot of different needs

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:02.160
popping up, different use cases.

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:04.800
So there's bound to be gaps discovered,

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:08.259
like the one that we discovered for production outputs,

00:03:09.720 --> 00:03:11.559
in particular, PDFs.

00:03:11.559 --> 00:03:14.080
And these are not just any PDF.

00:03:14.080 --> 00:03:17.199
They are rooted in years and years of tradition

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:20.000
and regulatory expectations.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:22.119
They have really finicky formatting

00:03:22.119 --> 00:03:24.759
and just a traditional appearance.

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:27.600
And out of that whole reporting process,

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.720
this is the thing that lands on the desks of stakeholders.

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:32.839
It's what they really care about,

00:03:32.839 --> 00:03:35.960
feeling very comfortable and familiar,

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:39.979
like they're sitting at home by the fire, right?

00:03:39.979 --> 00:03:43.440
So that's the job of DocCreator.

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:47.720
It's an R package that helps take an R-based display,

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.440
whether it's a table or a figure

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:51.240
or a lot of tables and figures,

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:56.000
and puts them in to a very traditional-looking output.

00:03:58.039 --> 00:04:01.559
And so that goal of feeling like home,

00:04:03.199 --> 00:04:05.440
that's the goal in these home renovation shows.

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:06.820
You wanna have a dream home in the end

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:09.279
that the client is super excited about.

00:04:09.279 --> 00:04:11.960
But it's not all smooth sailing.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:14.119
There's typically a little bit of drama

00:04:14.119 --> 00:04:17.760
along the way where there's some unexpected mold

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.440
or maybe there's a lot of duct issues.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:21.980
Lots of different challenges pop up.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:24.799
And there's still the original budget,

00:04:24.799 --> 00:04:27.559
the original timelines that need to be met.

00:04:27.559 --> 00:04:32.559
And when we discovered the gap for production outputs,

00:04:33.320 --> 00:04:37.359
we still needed to,

00:04:37.359 --> 00:04:39.920
we hadn't necessarily budgeted for that gap.

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:42.200
And when you have study teams

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:44.720
who are trying to meet their own deadlines,

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:46.160
if there's a gap, they will feel it

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.399
and they will try to solve it themselves.

00:04:48.399 --> 00:04:52.160
And all of a sudden, you have 10 different teams

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:53.839
creating 10 different workarounds, right?

00:04:53.839 --> 00:04:56.100
And it gets kind of crazy.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:04:58.279
So time was of the essence here.

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:02.799
So we took a look at what are the basic requirements,

00:05:02.799 --> 00:05:05.579
what are the absolute musts that we need to cover

00:05:05.579 --> 00:05:07.119
if we're building a solution,

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.679
and what tooling is already available for us

00:05:10.679 --> 00:05:12.459
to help us out.

00:05:12.459 --> 00:05:15.760
So taking a look at our traditional looking output,

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:18.320
first and foremost, GT compatibility.

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:21.920
So GT, the R package for making tables

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:24.040
developed by Rich from Posit.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.040
This is really, really important to Pharma.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:27.720
We use it a lot for tables.

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:30.559
It's very, very powerful with formatting.

00:05:30.559 --> 00:05:33.000
So whatever solution we created,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.399
we wanted to make sure it worked well with GT.

00:05:36.399 --> 00:05:37.839
Didn't want to disrupt that.

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:40.839
Headers and footers.

00:05:40.839 --> 00:05:42.600
These are really, really important,

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:47.600
part of this whole traditional appearance and traceability.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:51.440
So we want to know what study this table came from,

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:54.320
for instance, when the display was created,

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:55.160
things like that.

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:56.679
We want to have control over where

00:05:56.679 --> 00:05:58.920
this metadata goes as well.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.739
And finally, this one may seem obvious,

00:06:01.739 --> 00:06:04.600
but we want a workflow that's based in R.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:06.480
This is for a few reasons.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.359
One is we have some teams who are very, very new to R,

00:06:10.359 --> 00:06:13.200
so we don't want to throw another thing in.

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:15.519
We want to just kind of keep it consistent.

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:19.000
The other is we're, as developers,

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:20.880
we already have some tooling we're using

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:22.920
and developing in R.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.160
So if we're trying to build something very, very quickly,

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:27.679
we want to minimize the amount of change

00:06:27.679 --> 00:06:29.480
that we're making for ourselves

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:31.920
and make it easy to develop and maintain.

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:34.720
So, GT.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:36.760
I took this image from the website here.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:39.920
It just shows the workflow for GT.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:41.440
I think many of us know it by now,

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:44.160
but you start with your input data,

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:46.279
and then you work with it in R

00:06:46.279 --> 00:06:50.160
to create a nice formatted table using the GT package,

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:53.739
and you end up with an object that's in your R session

00:06:53.739 --> 00:06:57.399
that you're just kind of looking at in the RStudio viewer,

00:06:57.399 --> 00:07:01.420
and you can then save it out to a document if you like.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:03.239
And there's a few different choices.

00:07:03.239 --> 00:07:04.859
So we kind of thought,

00:07:04.859 --> 00:07:07.739
okay, what's going to get us closest to PDF?

00:07:07.739 --> 00:07:12.100
And if we consider the first option listed there, HTML,

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:14.299
Pharma's not quite ready for HTML yet.

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:17.579
We're still making our paginated displays.

00:07:17.579 --> 00:07:20.980
You could also, you could take an image,

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:24.619
like a screenshot of an HTML table

00:07:24.619 --> 00:07:26.859
and have a nice little pretty picture of it

00:07:26.859 --> 00:07:28.440
and put it in a PDF,

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:31.059
but traceability is very important for us.

00:07:31.739 --> 00:07:34.140
So we wanted to make sure our values

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:36.100
were embedded in that PDF.

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:40.700
So HTML was unfortunately off the table.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:45.700
RTF is something that has a pretty rich history in Pharma,

00:07:45.739 --> 00:07:48.200
so you could imagine that being an option,

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:52.739
but going from RTF to PDF is not, it's not easy or smooth.

00:07:52.739 --> 00:07:54.859
It's kind of a manual step.

00:07:54.859 --> 00:07:56.500
We don't want manual.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:58.459
So that leaves us with LaTeX,

00:07:58.459 --> 00:08:00.100
and we just heard about LaTeX from Keaton.

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:01.980
That was a nice primer.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:03.980
But LaTeX is a typesetting system

00:08:03.980 --> 00:08:07.179
that has been around for a long time,

00:08:07.179 --> 00:08:09.980
and once you get things into LaTeX,

00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:13.019
you're not quite to PDF, but you're very, very close.

00:08:13.019 --> 00:08:14.859
It just needs to be compiled,

00:08:14.859 --> 00:08:17.820
and that's a pretty, pretty simple step.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:21.540
So LaTeX puts us in the best position for PDF here.

00:08:23.820 --> 00:08:28.220
Speaking of LaTeX, there's a lot of libraries in LaTeX.

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:32.340
GT uses a few of those to format those tables,

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:35.659
so we took a look at what else might be available there,

00:08:35.659 --> 00:08:38.960
and you saw it flash up on the screen

00:08:38.960 --> 00:08:41.580
in the last presentation, but Fancy Header

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:45.099
is a pretty flexible LaTeX library

00:08:45.099 --> 00:08:48.460
for doing our headers and footers in different places,

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:50.140
in the top and bottom of the page,

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:53.299
with controlling all of those bits.

00:08:53.299 --> 00:08:56.820
So a really, really promising option for us.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:08:59.940
And making it placed in R.

00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:03.859
So we're already, our teams are already developing

00:09:03.859 --> 00:09:05.979
their tables in R, their figures in R,

00:09:05.979 --> 00:09:07.979
they're doing it in the R script.

00:09:07.979 --> 00:09:10.020
How are we gonna get them into the PDF?

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:13.340
And how does LaTeX come into play?

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:17.059
Well, that's where R Markdown and Corto come in.

00:09:17.059 --> 00:09:21.260
Instead of an R script, we can use these tools

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:26.260
to render a PDF directly through the PDF formatting engine,

00:09:26.299 --> 00:09:28.460
and under the hood, it's doing the LaTeX,

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:30.659
and so it makes it very easy for us

00:09:30.659 --> 00:09:33.280
to also throw in some LaTeX as well.

00:09:34.659 --> 00:09:36.780
So our basic requirements are met here,

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:39.580
and that's great, we have kind of all the pieces, right?

00:09:40.659 --> 00:09:42.659
But there's just one catch.

00:09:42.659 --> 00:09:45.419
It's that our teams are, you know,

00:09:45.419 --> 00:09:47.460
I've mentioned this a few times,

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:50.099
they may be learning a lot for the first time.

00:09:50.099 --> 00:09:53.780
And asking them to change from using an R script

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:56.380
and running things that way to all of a sudden

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:59.340
opening up a QMD and doing things a different way

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:01.619
is a change in process.

00:10:01.619 --> 00:10:04.219
And that's not necessarily something

00:10:04.219 --> 00:10:06.580
that's trivial to implement

00:10:07.659 --> 00:10:10.340
when there's already a lot of change going on.

00:10:10.340 --> 00:10:12.340
So we don't want these teams to have to do

00:10:12.340 --> 00:10:15.659
a bunch of maneuvers to use our solution,

00:10:15.659 --> 00:10:17.859
which is why we create a doc writer.

00:10:17.859 --> 00:10:21.979
We wrapped it all up, we took those bits and pieces,

00:10:22.059 --> 00:10:25.739
the R Markdown in Corto, the fancy header,

00:10:25.739 --> 00:10:28.900
the GT LaTeX conversion, all of those pieces

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:31.419
could come together and live in a package.

00:10:31.419 --> 00:10:35.099
And this is a parameterized report,

00:10:35.099 --> 00:10:38.020
so we're able to pass in that crucial metadata

00:10:38.020 --> 00:10:40.260
that can change from study to study

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.780
and make it all happen dynamically.

00:10:44.179 --> 00:10:46.179
So in practice, it looks something like this,

00:10:46.179 --> 00:10:50.380
where we have our original R script,

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:54.099
and we can, with a couple extra lines of code,

00:10:54.099 --> 00:10:57.500
pass or pipe our display right into

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.260
the doc writer function calls

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:01.419
and get a PDF on the other side.

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.859
If we look a little closer at these function calls,

00:11:05.859 --> 00:11:07.359
we have two here.

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:10.859
There's an as doc writer function and a render PDF.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.260
So as doc writer holds everything about our display.

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:18.299
The display itself, that render GT,

00:11:18.299 --> 00:11:20.340
as well as important metadata,

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:23.500
like the headers and footers and display name

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:25.419
and sizing things I don't show right here,

00:11:25.419 --> 00:11:29.640
but lots of key metadata that gets pulled together

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:31.780
and then passed to the rendering engine.

00:11:33.099 --> 00:11:35.140
Because headers and footers are so important,

00:11:35.140 --> 00:11:37.539
I wanted to zoom in even closer.

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:41.359
Here is our original display, just blown up a little bit,

00:11:41.359 --> 00:11:44.780
so we can see the headers more easily.

00:11:44.780 --> 00:11:46.859
So we have a couple lines of headers here

00:11:46.859 --> 00:11:50.140
that we can specify through the header argument

00:11:50.140 --> 00:11:52.580
and doc writer, and through the header argument

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:54.900
and doc writer, we use a fancy head function,

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:56.919
and this is totally an interface

00:11:56.919 --> 00:11:59.299
to the fancy header LaTeX library.

00:11:59.299 --> 00:12:03.859
And fancy head takes a series of fancy rows as an argument,

00:12:03.859 --> 00:12:06.739
so row by row in the header, you can say,

00:12:06.739 --> 00:12:08.820
what's my left, center, and right?

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:11.460
And so here, we want something on the left,

00:12:11.460 --> 00:12:14.419
the study name, we want some automatic page numbering

00:12:14.419 --> 00:12:17.599
on the right through our little helper.

00:12:17.599 --> 00:12:20.419
In the second row, we just want something on the left,

00:12:20.419 --> 00:12:23.940
the population, so we leave everything else empty.

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:25.159
And then in the final row,

00:12:25.159 --> 00:12:29.179
we want to put our centered table title.

00:12:29.179 --> 00:12:32.159
And so users can do this for the footer as well,

00:12:32.159 --> 00:12:34.619
it's a footer argument and ask doc writer,

00:12:34.619 --> 00:12:37.460
and a fancy foot function instead,

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:39.780
but all the row, fancy row stuff is the same,

00:12:39.780 --> 00:12:43.179
and they can just add in as many rows as they want

00:12:43.179 --> 00:12:45.260
within reason, because it will start

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:48.020
to kind of encroach on the display area.

00:12:50.039 --> 00:12:53.679
And this kind of flexibility is super important.

00:12:54.679 --> 00:12:57.940
We know that our user, when we went out

00:12:57.940 --> 00:12:59.539
to build the solution, we knew there was gonna be

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:02.979
a lot of different variations in formatting

00:13:02.979 --> 00:13:07.979
coming at the tool, and if you've ever built a tool

00:13:08.340 --> 00:13:11.020
and rolled it out before, you probably know

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:13.619
that people will start to throw things at it

00:13:13.619 --> 00:13:16.780
that you didn't expect, and it could break easily,

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:21.659
so we wanted to just avoid that situation as best we could.

00:13:21.659 --> 00:13:23.219
When we first did a release,

00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:24.979
we tried to cover the essentials,

00:13:24.979 --> 00:13:29.140
but make it easy to adapt as people gave us feedback,

00:13:29.140 --> 00:13:31.840
and we really tried to listen to them early and often.

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:34.659
And something that has come up,

00:13:34.659 --> 00:13:37.979
and we tried to get ahead of it quickly,

00:13:37.979 --> 00:13:40.859
is accommodating lots and lots of data,

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.820
lots of columns, many pages.

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:46.539
There's a lot of data to display,

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:51.260
and so we added some automated scaling

00:13:51.260 --> 00:13:54.020
for GT tables in particular.

00:13:54.020 --> 00:13:56.020
If a lot of columns are coming through,

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:59.299
we'll try to help make sure everything fits

00:13:59.299 --> 00:14:01.940
to the width on the page,

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:04.659
and also help with some proportional sizing

00:14:04.659 --> 00:14:09.659
of the left group and row data,

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:14.700
values that tend to be very text-heavy,

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:17.700
and then the numeric values in the rest of the columns,

00:14:17.700 --> 00:14:20.219
just try to help kind of even things out.

00:14:20.219 --> 00:14:21.979
If a user needs finer control,

00:14:21.979 --> 00:14:25.179
they can certainly do that through GT directly,

00:14:25.179 --> 00:14:28.940
and Dockerator will kind of assess the situation,

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:32.419
and will spit out some messages if things look a little,

00:14:32.419 --> 00:14:36.000
look like they might be a little bit of a weird result.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.020
So we hope to build this out even further,

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:40.400
just to keep it nice and user-friendly.

00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:44.099
We also realized pretty early on

00:14:44.099 --> 00:14:48.820
that our framework was generalizable,

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:52.820
and useful in other scenarios for other document types.

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:54.619
So we care a lot about PDFs,

00:14:54.619 --> 00:14:59.619
but there's other things that need to be made,

00:15:00.260 --> 00:15:02.400
not just for us, but for others as well,

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:06.059
and so we started with just a render PDF function

00:15:06.059 --> 00:15:08.940
that was kind of all Dockerator did in the beginning,

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:12.099
and we decided to break it into pieces,

00:15:12.099 --> 00:15:15.219
and that's where the asDockerator function came to be.

00:15:15.219 --> 00:15:19.340
So we split up Dockerator creation, rendering,

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:22.580
and produced an intermediate Dockerator object,

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:25.820
and optionally a permanent file as well.

00:15:25.820 --> 00:15:27.659
And so that holds the display itself,

00:15:27.659 --> 00:15:29.700
and all of that important metadata

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:33.419
that can be picked up and reused in different templates.

00:15:33.419 --> 00:15:35.059
So we have a couple templates now,

00:15:35.059 --> 00:15:38.419
the original PDF, the RTF,

00:15:38.419 --> 00:15:42.979
which is kind of very basic compared to the PDF,

00:15:42.979 --> 00:15:45.380
but it's in a position now,

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:49.919
the framework, that it could expand to future output types,

00:15:49.919 --> 00:15:52.260
just need the template for it.

00:15:54.940 --> 00:15:59.140
The ability to evolve is really, really important as well,

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:03.419
and so we wanna be able to take our framework

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:06.099
and adapt it as technologies change,

00:16:06.099 --> 00:16:08.619
as new things come in,

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:10.580
much like if you're doing the kitchen part

00:16:10.580 --> 00:16:11.659
of your home renovation,

00:16:11.659 --> 00:16:14.580
you might make certain aesthetic choices today

00:16:14.580 --> 00:16:16.700
that you, you know, the white countertops

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:18.340
and cabinets and everything.

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:19.799
Five, 10 years from now,

00:16:19.799 --> 00:16:21.820
that may not be what you want anymore,

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:23.739
there may be totally different trends.

00:16:23.739 --> 00:16:27.280
And so with Corto in particular,

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:30.479
we're well-poised to adapt to these trends.

00:16:31.479 --> 00:16:34.280
Something like Dockerator for Python may be useful one day,

00:16:34.280 --> 00:16:36.559
and so it's an easier transition

00:16:36.559 --> 00:16:38.260
to building something like that.

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:42.159
And, you know, today we're using LaTeX,

00:16:42.159 --> 00:16:46.599
which is a little bit finicky with the syntax,

00:16:47.840 --> 00:16:52.159
it comes with the burden of system dependencies as well,

00:16:52.159 --> 00:16:54.760
so like Keaton, we're looking forward

00:16:54.760 --> 00:16:57.599
to the capabilities of types,

00:16:57.599 --> 00:17:01.159
it's a little bit of early days with GT,

00:17:01.159 --> 00:17:02.799
and because that's so important to us,

00:17:02.799 --> 00:17:04.439
we're not quite there,

00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:06.880
but, you know, looking forward to that

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:10.699
potentially being a better option down the line,

00:17:10.699 --> 00:17:12.839
and having, you know,

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:17.300
just a smoother maintenance process as well.

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:19.119
And something I'm pretty excited about with types

00:17:19.119 --> 00:17:21.520
is branding, you know,

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:23.099
I've talked up a lot about how we care

00:17:23.099 --> 00:17:25.040
about that traditional appearance,

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:27.680
but hopefully that will evolve as well, right?

00:17:28.599 --> 00:17:29.760
And so with branding,

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:32.359
we can take things like our fancy dashboards,

00:17:32.359 --> 00:17:33.959
and we can do something similar

00:17:33.959 --> 00:17:35.959
between our PDFs and our dashboards

00:17:35.959 --> 00:17:37.640
and our websites and things like that,

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.199
and maybe one day our stakeholders

00:17:40.199 --> 00:17:43.160
will be very excited for pumpkin spice season,

00:17:43.160 --> 00:17:45.880
and they'll wanna do something fun like this.

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:48.439
But all that to say,

00:17:48.439 --> 00:17:53.439
Dockerator has been kind of the missing piece of the puzzle,

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:55.719
the final proof of confidence

00:17:55.719 --> 00:17:58.479
that R can really be used end to end

00:17:58.479 --> 00:18:01.199
and create that final output.

00:18:01.199 --> 00:18:05.040
So it's been very, very useful for us,

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:09.760
and, you know, we noticed the gap in open source,

00:18:09.760 --> 00:18:13.119
and so it was important for us to fill it

00:18:13.119 --> 00:18:14.680
back into the open source.

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:18.119
You can find Dockerator on our GitHub page,

00:18:18.119 --> 00:18:19.119
here's the website,

00:18:19.119 --> 00:18:21.359
we're working on a CRAN submission now,

00:18:21.359 --> 00:18:25.160
and likely a Pharmaverse submission as well

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:26.359
to contribute that back.

00:18:26.359 --> 00:18:28.199
